'''Satō Jōjitsu''' (佐藤 誠実, also read as Satō Nobuzane; December 28, 1839 – March 31, 1908) was a Japanese scholar of [[Kokugaku]] (national studies) from the late [[Edo period]] to the [[Meiji period]].
== Biography == Satō was born at {{ill|Shogyōji Temple (Taitō Ward)|ja|正行寺 (台東区)|12=draft}}, a Jōdo Shinshū temple in {{ill|Asakusa|ja|浅草|12=draft}}, [[Edo]] (present-day {{ill|Taitō Ward|ja|台東区|12=draft}}, [[Tokyo]]). His childhood name was Zōshu, and his pseudonym was Mokuzai.
From a young age, he served as the head priest of his family temple. He later studied Chinese classics under {{ill|Azumi Gonsai|ja|安積艮斎|12=draft}} and Kokugaku under {{ill|Kurokawa Harumura|ja|黒川春村|12=draft}}.
After the [[Meiji Restoration]], in 1872, he joined the [[Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology|Ministry of Education]] (then known as the Ministry of Education). Later, he worked at the {{ill|Genrōin|ja|元老院 (日本)|12=draft}}, a precursor to the [[Imperial Diet (Japan)|Imperial Diet]].
In 1880, he contributed to the compilation of the ''{{ill|Kojiruien|ja|古事類苑|12=draft}}'', a comprehensive encyclopedic work, alongside {{ill|Hiroike Chikurō|ja|廣池千九郎|12=draft}}. When the project was transferred to the [[Jingū Administration Office]] in 1895, he was appointed as the chief editor.
In recognition of his contributions, he was awarded the title of [[Doctor of Letters (Japan)|Doctor of Letters]] in 1899.
== Academic Career == In 1883, he became a lecturer in the classics department at [[Tokyo University]] (later {{ill|Tokyo Imperial University|ja|東京帝国大学|12=draft}}), and in 1891, he was appointed a professor of classical studies at the {{ill|Tokyo Music School (former)|ja|東京音楽学校 (旧制)|12=draft}}.
