'''Satō Jōjitsu''' (佐藤 誠実, also read as Satō Nobuzane; December 28, 1839 – March 31, 1908) was a Japanese scholar of [[:en:Kokugaku|Kokugaku]] (national studies) from the late [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]] to the [[Meiji period]].
== Biography == Satō was born at {{ill|Shogyōji Temple (Taitō Ward)|ja|正行寺 (台東区)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shogyōji Temple (Taitō Ward)|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, a Jōdo Shinshū temple in [[:en:Asakusa|Asakusa]], [[:en:Edo|Edo]] (present-day [[:en:Taitō|Taitō Ward]], [[Tokyo]]). His childhood name was Zōshu, and his pseudonym was Mokuzai.
From a young age, he served as the head priest of his family temple. He later studied Chinese classics under {{ill|Azumi Gonsai|ja|安積艮斎|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Azumi Gonsai|qq=}} and Kokugaku under {{ill|Kurokawa Harumura|ja|黒川春村|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kurokawa Harumura|qq=}}.
After the [[Meiji Restoration]], in 1872, he joined the [[Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology|Ministry of Education]] (then known as the Ministry of Education). Later, he worked at the [[:en:Genrōin|Genrōin]], a precursor to the [[:en:Imperial Diet (Japan)|Imperial Diet]].
In 1880, he contributed to the compilation of the ''[[:en:Koji Ruien|Kojiruien]]'', a comprehensive encyclopedic work, alongside {{ill|Hiroike Chikurō|ja|廣池千九郎|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiroike Chikurō|qq=}}. When the project was transferred to the [[Jingū Administration Office]] in 1895, he was appointed as the chief editor.
In recognition of his contributions, he was awarded the title of [[Doctor of Letters (Japan)|Doctor of Letters]] in 1899.
== Academic Career == In 1883, he became a lecturer in the classics department at [[Tokyo University]] (later {{ill|Tokyo Imperial University|ja|東京帝国大学|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokyo Imperial University|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 東京大学}}), and in 1891, he was appointed a professor of classical studies at the {{ill|Tokyo Music School (former)|ja|東京音楽学校 (旧制)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokyo Music School (former)|qq=}}.
